        t.addLesson(new Lesson("3. Weighted averages (unequal groups)", "<p>A plain average treats every value as equally important. But if a class has 30 boys and only 20 girls, the boys' average should count <em>more</em>. That's a <strong>weighted average</strong>.</p>" + Doc.formula("Weighted avg = (n\u2081\u00d7A\u2081 + n\u2082\u00d7A\u2082) \u00f7 (n\u2081 + n\u2082)") + Doc.analogy("Your final grade where the exam is worth more than homework is a weighted average \u2014 the heavier item tugs the result toward its own value.") + Doc.example("30 boys average 40 kg, 20 girls average 35 kg. Class average?", "Total weight = 30\u00d740 + 20\u00d735 = 1200 + 700 = 1900 kg. Total people = 50. Average = 1900 \u00f7 50 = <strong>38 kg</strong>. Notice it's closer to 40 than 35, because there are more boys.") + Doc.warn("Don't just average the two averages ((40+35)\u00f72 = 37.5). That's only correct if the groups are the <em>same size</em>.") + Doc.recap("Weight each average by its group size: multiply, add, then divide by the total count."), 3));
        t.addLesson(new Lesson("4. Mixtures and the alligation rule", "<p>Mixing two things of different price or strength to hit a target value is just a weighted average run backwards. <strong>Alligation</strong> gives the mixing ratio quickly.</p>" + Doc.formula("(quantity of cheap) : (quantity of dear) = (dear \u2212 mean) : (mean \u2212 cheap)") + "<p>Think of alligation as a shortcut for balancing total value. The target mean must lie between the two source values; otherwise the mixture is impossible.</p>" + Doc.analogy("To make lukewarm water, you mix hot and cold. The closer the target is to \u2018cold\u2019, the more cold water you need. Alligation measures exactly how much of each.") + Doc.example("Mix rice at 30/kg with rice at 45/kg to get a mixture at 40/kg. In what ratio?", "Cheap = 30, dear = 45, mean = 40.<br>Cheap : dear = (45\u221240) : (40\u221230) = 5 : 10 = <strong>1 : 2</strong>. So twice as much of the costlier rice (since 40 is nearer 45).") + Doc.example("Milk-water blend", "Pure milk has value 100%, water has 0%. For a 70% milk target:<br>water : milk = (100\u221270):(70\u22120) = 30:70 = <strong>3:7</strong>.") + "<h4>When quantities are asked</h4>" + Doc.steps("First find the ratio by alligation.", "Convert ratio parts to real quantities using the given total quantity.", "Check by recomputing the weighted average to verify the target mean.") + Doc.warn("Don't reverse the ratio by mistake: cheap side uses (dear-mean), dear side uses (mean-cheap).") + Doc.tip("The ingredient whose value is <em>closer</em> to the target is the one you use <em>more</em> of. Use this to check your ratio points the right way.") + Doc.recap("Alligation: distances from the mean give the mixing ratio (cross them over). Closer to target \u2192 used in larger amount."), 4));
        t.addLesson(new Lesson("5. Median and mode: other kinds of 'middle'", "<p>The average (mean) is only one way to describe a 'typical' value. Two more are very useful, especially when a few extreme values would distort the mean.</p><h4>Median \u2014 the middle value</h4><p>Line the numbers up in order; the <strong>median</strong> is the one in the middle. If there is an even count, average the two middle ones.</p>" + Doc.example("Median of 3, 7, 9, 12, 20", "Already in order; the middle (3rd of 5) is <strong>9</strong>.") + "<h4>Mode \u2014 the most common value</h4><p>The <strong>mode</strong> is the value that appears most often.</p>" + Doc.analogy("If you ask everyone's favourite ice-cream and 'vanilla' wins most votes, vanilla is the mode \u2014 the crowd favourite, not an 'average flavour'.") + Doc.warn("A single huge value (an outlier) can drag the mean far from the centre, but barely moves the median. That's why house prices are usually reported as a median.") + Doc.recap("Mean = balance point, Median = middle of the sorted list, Mode = most frequent value."), 5));
